"**If You 're Not the One**" is a song by English singer [Daniel
Bedingfield](/wiki/Daniel_Bedingfield "Daniel Bedingfield"). It was released
on 25 November 2002 as the third single from his debut studio album _[Gotta
Get Thru This](/wiki/Gotta_Get_Thru_This_\(album\) "Gotta Get Thru This
\(album\)")_ (2002).

The single entered the top 20 on the majority of charts that it appeared on,
including being a number-one hit in the [UK Singles
Chart](/wiki/UK_Singles_Chart "UK Singles Chart"),[1] and reaching number 15
in the [United States](/wiki/Billboard_Hot_100 "Billboard Hot 100").

## Background and
writing[[edit](/w/index.php?title=If_You%27re_Not_the_One&action=edit&section=1
"Edit section: Background and writing")]

"If You're Not the One" is written as a love ballad.[2] Bedingfield claims to
have been inspired by the band [Westlife](/wiki/Westlife "Westlife"), when
writing and recording the song.[3] Bedingfield himself believes that the song
is "cheesy."[4] Bedingfield admitted he began writing the song because he
realized that material he considered more "complex", was unlikely to get him a
record deal.[4] "Commercialism, sappy lyrics and meek tunes are the things I
hate most in the universe, but I'm not sure even Bob Dylan could get record
company interest without hooks these days", Bedingfield recalled in an
interview with _[The Daily Telegraph](/wiki/The_Daily_Telegraph "The Daily
Telegraph")_.[4] "It's a different age. You need to go some kind of populist
route. So, about three years ago, I sat down with a Westlife song and tried to
write something similar."[4]

Bedingfield also admitted that he didn't even want to put the song on his
album.[5] He said, "I didn't want to put "If You're Not the One" on the album
as I thought it was too cheesy. I thought it sounded like Westlife. But she
([Natasha Bedingfield](/wiki/Natasha_Bedingfield "Natasha Bedingfield"), his
sister) loved it. Women that hear it go all soft and think it's lovely"[5]

##
Composition[[edit](/w/index.php?title=If_You%27re_Not_the_One&action=edit&section=2
"Edit section: Composition")]

"If You're Not the One" plays for 4 minutes and 19 seconds, in [common
time](/wiki/Common_time "Common time"). It is in the key of [B-flat
major](/wiki/B-flat_major "B-flat major"), and the chorus features Bedingfield
singing [falsetto](/wiki/Falsetto "Falsetto"), where he hits the note
[E♭5](/wiki/E%E2%99%AD_\(musical_note\) "E♭ \(musical note\)").[6]

## Critical
reception[[edit](/w/index.php?title=If_You%27re_Not_the_One&action=edit&section=3
"Edit section: Critical reception")]

"If You're Not the One" received mixed reviews from contemporary music
critics. On the positive side, Peter Robinson, in the _Gotta Get thru This_
album review for the _[New Musical Express](/wiki/NME "NME")_ (_NME_), wrote
"If You're Not the One [recalls] every chart-mauling uber-ballad you've ever
heard".[7] Nedd Raggett of [AllMusic](/wiki/AllMusic "AllMusic") commented in
his album review "When it comes to ballads, they work best in sudden moments –
the soaring end to If You're Not the One".[8] [About.com](/wiki/About.com
"About.com") ranked the song at number 27 on its list of the 'Top 100 Pop
Songs of 2002', two places behind the [album's title
track](/wiki/Gotta_Get_Thru_This_\(song\) "Gotta Get Thru This \(song\)").[9]
The song was again ranked at number 27 on the 2003 list, due to it being
released in the United States during that year.[10] _Music Week_ felt that the
song showed Bedingfield's "sensitive side", and that the song "showcases his
vocal range to stunning effect."[2] The magazine even considered it
"beautifully crafted."[2]

However, the track also received some negative feedback.
_[PopMatters](/wiki/PopMatters "PopMatters")_ ' Nikki Tranter wrote "surely
you would think with his obviously overwhelming ability to compose utter
claptrap cleverly disguised as serious prophesizing, his lyrics might contain
something a little more expressive than 'If you're not the one / Why does my
heart feel glad today / If you're not the one / Then why does my hand fit
yours this way.'"[11] In his review for [musicOMH](/wiki/MusicOMH "MusicOMH"),
Michael Hubbard was even less positive, stating, "If You're Not the One is as
vomit-inducing as anything the man in the plastic mask has ever wretched
_([sic](/wiki/Sic "Sic"))_ forth at the world".[12]

## Chart
performance[[edit](/w/index.php?title=If_You%27re_Not_the_One&action=edit&section=4
"Edit section: Chart performance")]

When the song was released as a single, it was picked up by radio stations. It
was the most added pop song on the radio for the week of 20 February 2003.[13]
In the US, the song was the most added song in the Adult Contemporary market
for the week of 7 April 2003.[14] In the US, the song was his highest debuting
single, debuting at number 55 on the [_Billboard_ Hot
100](/wiki/Billboard_Hot_100 "Billboard Hot 100").[14] The single proved to be
a successful release for Bedingfield, providing him with several worldwide
number ones and reaching the top 20 in all but one of the charts that it
appeared on. It debuted at number one in the [UK Singles
Chart](/wiki/UK_Singles_Chart "UK Singles Chart"), knocking [Christina
Aguilera](/wiki/Christina_Aguilera "Christina Aguilera")'s
"[Dirrty](/wiki/Dirrty "Dirrty")" from the top spot.[15]

## Music
video[[edit](/w/index.php?title=If_You%27re_Not_the_One&action=edit&section=5
"Edit section: Music video")]

The music video was produced by [A1](/wiki/A1_\(band\) "A1 \(band\)") singer
[Mark Read](/wiki/Mark_Read_\(singer\) "Mark Read \(singer\)"). It begins with
a series of images of Bedingfield singing in various positions against a black
backdrop. When the chorus starts he is seen singing with clouds in the
background. The initial sequence is repeated for the second verse. However,
half-way through, he starts to write on a wall. The rest of the song follows
the same pattern.
